{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_14","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/zsh -lc \"sed -n '1,260p' src/gguf/header.HC && sed -n '1,260p' src/gguf/tensorinfo.HC\"","aggregated_output":"// header.HC\n// GGUF header parser for HolyC inference runtime.\n\n#define GGUF_MAGIC_U32 0x46554747\n#define GGUF_VERSION_V2 2\n#define GGUF_VERSION_V3 3\n\n#define GGUF_PARSE_OK 0\n#define GGUF_PARSE_ERR_NULL_PTR 1\n#define GGUF_PARSE_ERR_TRUNCATED 2\n#define GGUF_PARSE_ERR_BAD_MAGIC 3\n#define GGUF_PARSE_ERR_BAD_VERSION 4\n#define GGUF_PARSE_ERR_BAD_COUNT 5\n\nclass GGUFHeader\n{\n    U32 magic;\n    U32 version;\n    U64 tensor_count;\n    U64 metadata_kv_count;\n};\n\nBool GGUFCanRead(U8 *buf, I64 size, I64 cursor, I64 need)\n{\n    if (!buf)\n        return FALSE;\n    if (size < 0 || cursor < 0 || need < 0)\n        return FALSE;\n    if (cursor > size)\n        return FALSE;\n    if (need > size - cursor)\n        return FALSE;\n    return TRUE;\n}\n\nBool GGUFReadU32LE(U8 *buf, I64 size, I64 *cursor, U32 *out)\n{\n    I64 c;\n\n    if (!cursor || !out)\n        return FALSE;\n\n    c = *cursor;\n    if (!GGUFCanRead(buf, size, c, 4))\n        return FALSE;\n\n    *out = (U32)buf[c]\n         | ((U32)buf[c + 1] << 8)\n         | ((U32)buf[c + 2] << 16)\n         | ((U32)buf[c + 3] << 24);\n\n    *cursor = c + 4;\n    return TRUE;\n}\n\nBool GGUFReadU64LE(U8 *buf, I64 size, I64 *cursor, U64 *out)\n{\n    I64 c;\n\n    if (!cursor || !out)\n        return FALSE;\n\n    c = *cursor;\n    if (!GGUFCanRead(buf, size, c, 8))\n        return FALSE;\n\n    *out = (U64)buf[c]\n         | ((U64)buf[c + 1] << 8)\n         | ((U64)buf[c + 2] << 16)\n         | ((U64)buf[c + 3] << 24)\n         | ((U64)buf[c + 4] << 32)\n         | ((U64)buf[c + 5] << 40)\n         | ((U64)buf[c + 6] << 48)\n         | ((U64)buf[c + 7] << 56);\n\n    *cursor = c + 8;\n    return TRUE;\n}\n\nI64 GGUFParseHeader(U8 *buf, I64 size, GGUFHeader *out, I64 *cursor)\n{\n    I64 c;\n    U32 magic;\n    U32 version;\n    U64 tensor_count;\n    U64 metadata_kv_count;\n\n    if (!buf || !out || !cursor)\n        return GGUF_PARSE_ERR_NULL_PTR;\n\n    c = *cursor;\n\n    if (!GGUFReadU32LE(buf, size, &c, &magic))\n        return GGUF_PARSE_ERR_TRUNCATED;\n    if (magic != GGUF_MAGIC_U32)\n        return GGUF_PARSE_ERR_BAD_MAGIC;\n\n    if (!GGUFReadU32LE(buf, size, &c, &version))\n        return GGUF_PARSE_ERR_TRUNCATED;\n    if (version != GGUF_VERSION_V2 && version != GGUF_VERSION_V3)\n        return GGUF_PARSE_ERR_BAD_VERSION;\n\n    if (!GGUFReadU64LE(buf, size, &c, &tensor_count))\n        return GGUF_PARSE_ERR_TRUNCATED;\n    if (!GGUFReadU64LE(buf, size, &c, &metadata_kv_count))\n        return GGUF_PARSE_ERR_TRUNCATED;\n\n    if (!tensor_count)\n        return GGUF_PARSE_ERR_BAD_COUNT;\n\n    out->magic = magic;\n    out->version = version;\n    out->tensor_count = tensor_count;\n    out->metadata_kv_count = metadata_kv_count;\n\n    *cursor = c;\n    return GGUF_PARSE_OK;\n}\n// tensorinfo.HC\n// GGUF tensor info table parser for HolyC inference runtime.\n\n#define GGUF_TENSOR_PARSE_OK 0\n#define GGUF_TENSOR_PARSE_ERR_NULL_PTR 1\n#define GGUF_TENSOR_PARSE_ERR_TRUNCATED 2\n#define GGUF_TENSOR_PARSE_ERR_BAD_COUNT 3\n#define GGUF_TENSOR_PARSE_ERR_BAD_NAME_LEN 4\n#define GGUF_TENSOR_PARSE_ERR_BAD_DIMS 5\n#define GGUF_TENSOR_PARSE_ERR_BAD_DIM_SIZE 6\n#define GGUF_TENSOR_PARSE_ERR_DIM_OVERFLOW 7\n#define GGUF_TENSOR_PARSE_ERR_BAD_TYPE 8\n#define GGUF_TENSOR_PARSE_ERR_ALLOC 9\n\n#define GGUF_TENSOR_MAX_COUNT     (1 << 20)\n#define GGUF_TENSOR_MAX_NAME_BYTES (1 << 20)\n#define GGUF_TENSOR_MAX_DIMS      8\n\n// Common ggml tensor types used in GGUF today. Parser is strict so bad type tags\n// are rejected early and never reach tensor byte-loader math.\n#define GGML_TYPE_F32   0\n#define GGML_TYPE_F16   1\n#define GGML_TYPE_Q4_0  2\n#define GGML_TYPE_Q4_1  3\n#define GGML_TYPE_Q5_0  6\n#define GGML_TYPE_Q5_1  7\n#define GGML_TYPE_Q8_0  8\n#define GGML_TYPE_Q8_1  9\n#define GGML_TYPE_Q2_K  10\n#define GGML_TYPE_Q3_K  11\n#define GGML_TYPE_Q4_K  12\n#define GGML_TYPE_Q5_K  13\n#define GGML_TYPE_Q6_K  14\n#define GGML_TYPE_Q8_K  15\n#define GGML_TYPE_IQ2_XXS 16\n#define GGML_TYPE_IQ2_XS  17\n#define GGML_TYPE_IQ3_XXS 18\n#define GGML_TYPE_IQ1_S   19\n#define GGML_TYPE_IQ4_NL  20\n#define GGML_TYPE_IQ3_S   21\n#define GGML_TYPE_IQ2_S   22\n#define GGML_TYPE_IQ4_XS  23\n#define GGML_TYPE_I8    24\n#define GGML_TYPE_I16   25\n#define GGML_TYPE_I32   26\n#define GGML_TYPE_I64   27\n#define GGML_TYPE_F64   28\n#define GGML_TYPE_IQ1_M 29\n#define GGML_TYPE_BF16  30\n#define GGML_TYPE_Q4_0_4_4 31\n#define GGML_TYPE_Q4_0_4_8 32\n#define GGML_TYPE_Q4_0_8_8 33\n#define GGML_TYPE_TQ1_0 34\n#define GGML_TYPE_TQ2_0 35\n\nclass GGUFTensorString\n{\n    U64 len;\n    U8 *data;\n};\n\nclass GGUFTensorInfo\n{\n    GGUFTensorString name;\n\n    U32 n_dims;\n    U64 dims[GGUF_TENSOR_MAX_DIMS];\n    U64 n_elements;\n\n    U32 ggml_type;\n    U64 offset;\n};\n\nclass GGUFTensorTable\n{\n    U64 count;\n    GGUFTensorInfo *items;\n};\n\nBool GGUFTensorCanRead(U8 *buf, I64 size, I64 cursor, I64 need)\n{\n    if (!buf)\n        return FALSE;\n    if (size < 0 || cursor < 0 || need < 0)\n        return FALSE;\n    if (cursor > size)\n        return FALSE;\n    if (need > size - cursor)\n        return FALSE;\n    return TRUE;\n}\n\nBool GGUFTensorReadU32LE(U8 *buf, I64 size, I64 *cursor, U32 *out)\n{\n    I64 c;\n\n    if (!cursor || !out)\n        return FALSE;\n\n    c = *cursor;\n    if (!GGUFTensorCanRead(buf, size, c, 4))\n        return FALSE;\n\n    *out = (U32)buf[c]\n         | ((U32)buf[c + 1] << 8)\n         | ((U32)buf[c + 2] << 16)\n         | ((U32)buf[c + 3] << 24);\n\n    *cursor = c + 4;\n    return TRUE;\n}\n\nBool GGUFTensorReadU64LE(U8 *buf, I64 size, I64 *cursor, U64 *out)\n{\n    I64 c;\n\n    if (!cursor || !out)\n        return FALSE;\n\n    c = *cursor;\n    if (!GGUFTensorCanRead(buf, size, c, 8))\n        return FALSE;\n\n    *out = (U64)buf[c]\n         | ((U64)buf[c + 1] << 8)\n         | ((U64)buf[c + 2] << 16)\n         | ((U64)buf[c + 3] << 24)\n         | ((U64)buf[c + 4] << 32)\n         | ((U64)buf[c + 5] << 40)\n         | ((U64)buf[c + 6] << 48)\n         | ((U64)buf[c + 7] << 56);\n\n    *cursor = c + 8;\n    return TRUE;\n}\n\nBool GGUFTensorTypeKnown(U32 t)\n{\n    switch (t)\n    {\n        case GGML_TYPE_F32:\n        case GGML_TYPE_F16:\n        case GGML_TYPE_Q4_0:\n        case GGML_TYPE_Q4_1:\n        case GGML_TYPE_Q5_0:\n        case GGML_TYPE_Q5_1:\n        case GGML_TYPE_Q8_0:\n        case GGML_TYPE_Q8_1:\n        case GGML_TYPE_Q2_K:\n        case GGML_TYPE_Q3_K:\n        case GGML_TYPE_Q4_K:\n        case GGML_TYPE_Q5_K:\n        case GGML_TYPE_Q6_K:\n        case GGML_TYPE_Q8_K:\n        case GGML_TYPE_IQ2_XXS:\n        case GGML_TYPE_IQ2_XS:\n        case GGML_TYPE_IQ3_XXS:\n        case GGML_TYPE_IQ1_S:\n        case GGML_TYPE_IQ4_NL:\n        case GGML_TYPE_IQ3_S:\n        case GGML_TYPE_IQ2_S:\n        case GGML_TYPE_IQ4_XS:\n        case GGML_TYPE_I8:\n        case GGML_TYPE_I16:\n        case GGML_TYPE_I32:\n        case GGML_TYPE_I64:\n        case GGML_TYPE_F64:\n        case GGML_TYPE_IQ1_M:\n        case GGML_TYPE_BF16:\n        case GGML_TYPE_Q4_0_4_4:\n        case GGML_TYPE_Q4_0_4_8:\n        case GGML_TYPE_Q4_0_8_8:\n        case GGML_TYPE_TQ1_0:\n        case GGML_TYPE_TQ2_0:\n            return TRUE;\n    }\n\n    return FALSE;\n}\n\nU0 GGUFTensorZeroString(GGUFTensorString *s)\n{\n    if (!s)\n        return;\n    s->len = 0;\n    s->data = NULL;\n}\n\nU0 GGUFTensorZeroInfo(GGUFTensorInfo *ti)\n{\n    I64 i;\n\n    if (!ti)\n        return;\n\n    GGUFTensorZeroString(&ti->name);\n    ti->n_dims = 0;\n    for (i = 0; i < GGUF_TENSOR_MAX_DIMS; ++i)\n        ti->dims[i] = 0;\n    ti->n_elements = 0;\n    ti->ggml_type = 0;\n    ti->offset = 0;\n}\n\nU0 GGUFTensorFreeString(GGUFTensorString *s)\n{\n    if (!s)\n        return;\n\n    if (s->data)\n        Free(s->data);\n\n    s->data = NULL;\n    s->len = 0;\n}\n\nU0 GGUFFreeTensorTable(GGUFTensorTable *table)\n{\n    U64 i;\n\n    if (!table)\n        return;\n\n    if (!table->items)\n    {\n        table->count = 0;\n        return;\n    }\n\n    for (i = 0; i < table->count; ++i)\n        GGUFTensorFreeString(&table->items[i].name);\n\n    Free(table->items);\n    table->items = NULL;\n    table->count = 0;\n}\n\nI64 GGUFTensorReadString(U8 *buf, I64 size, I64 *cursor, GGUFTensorString *out)\n{\n    U64 len;\n    I64 c;\n    U8 *dst;\n    I64 i;\n\n    if (!cursor || !out)\n        return GGUF_TENSOR_PARSE_ERR_NULL_PTR;\n\n    GGUFTensorZeroString(out);\n\n    if (!GGUFTensorReadU64LE(buf, size, cursor, &len))\n        return GGUF_TENSOR_PARSE_ERR_TRUNCATED;\n    if (len > GGUF_TENSOR_MAX_NAME_BYTES)\n        return GGUF_TENSOR_PARSE_ERR_BAD_NAME_LEN;\n\n    c = *cursor;\n    if (!GGUFTensorCanRead(buf, size, c, len))\n        return GGUF_TENSOR_PARSE_ERR_TRUNCATED;\n\n    dst = MAlloc(len + 1);\n    if (!dst)\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
{"type":"item.started","item":{"id":"item_15","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/zsh -lc \"sed -n '1,220p' ~/Documents/local-codebases/temple-sanhedrin/research/2026-04-12-q32-intermediate-precision.md && sed -n '1,220p' ~/Documents/local-codebases/temple-sanhedrin/research/2026-04-12-kernel-vertical-slice-guidance.md\"","aggregated_output":"","exit_code":null,"status":"in_progress"}}
{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_15","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/zsh -lc \"sed -n '1,220p' ~/Documents/local-codebases/temple-sanhedrin/research/2026-04-12-q32-intermediate-precision.md && sed -n '1,220p' ~/Documents/local-codebases/temple-sanhedrin/research/2026-04-12-kernel-vertical-slice-guidance.md\"","aggregated_output":"# Research Directive: Q32 Intermediate Precision for Accumulator Path\n\n## Trigger\nThe inference engine uses Q16 (16-bit fixed-point) for all math. When chaining through 22+ transformer layers, each layer's ~1% error compounds to ~24% drift. The accumulator path in matmul and attention needs wider precision.\n\n## Research Required\nThe Sanhedrin MUST research and document:\n\n1. **GGML's actual accumulator width** — what does llama.cpp use for intermediate sums in quantized dot products? (Hint: it uses 32-bit integer accumulators for Q4_0/Q8_0 dot products)\n\n2. **Q32 fixed-point design** — define a Q16.16 or Q8.24 format for intermediate tensor values. The final output per layer can be downscaled back to Q16, but matmul inner loops and attention score accumulation should stay Q32.\n\n3. **Where to widen** — identify the exact code paths in the inference engine that need Q32:\n   - `Q4_0DotProductBlocksQ32` accumulator (src/quant/q4_0_dot.HC)\n   - `Q8_0DotProductBlocksQ32` accumulator (src/quant/q8_0_dot.HC)\n   - Matmul output accumulation (WS4, not yet built)\n   - Attention score computation before softmax (WS5-02)\n   - RMSNorm variance accumulation (src/math/rmsnorm.HC)\n\n4. **Overflow analysis** — for a 4096-dim dot product with Q32 accumulator, what's the max possible value? Does it fit in I64? (4096 * 127 * 127 * 65536 = ~4.2e15, fits in I64 which holds 9.2e18)\n\n## Action\nWrite findings to this file. The inference agent reads Sanhedrin research/ directory each iteration.\n# Research Note — Kernel Vertical Slice Guidance (2026-04-12)\n\n## Why this note exists\nTempleOS modernization shows a long doc-only streak, which risks architecture drift and delayed executable validation. This note gives authoritative references for a tighter implementation cadence.\n\n## Primary references\n- OSDev Wiki — *Creating an Operating System*: practical bring-up order from toolchain/boot to runnable kernel slices.\n- OSDev Wiki — *Bare Bones* and *Paging*: incremental, testable boot-to-kernel progression and MMU foundations.\n- xv6 book (MIT PDOS): chapter ordering (traps/interrupts/locking/scheduling/filesystem) demonstrates proven vertical-slice pedagogy.\n- seL4 docs — *Verified Configurations*: emphasizes artifact-backed kernel outputs and configuration-specific correctness checks.\n- QEMU system manpage/docs: canonical runtime flags and machine options (including no-network execution policies).\n- ggml `docs/gguf.md`: source-of-truth GGUF layout and extensibility model for parser/kernel-interface alignment.\n\n## Practical directives for the builder loops\n1. Switch from “spec breadth” to “executable thin slices”: each iteration should produce one runnable/parsable artifact or one deterministic validation output.\n2. Enforce a strict slice chain for modernization work:\n   - boot + trap entry\n   - page-table mutation path + synchronous Book-of-Truth write\n   - scheduler tick path + synchronous Book-of-Truth write\n   - syscall path + synchronous Book-of-Truth write\n3. Treat docs as support artifacts only: every doc update must be paired with either:\n   - HolyC code touched in core paths, or\n   - a failing/then-passing harness check tied to a concrete invariant.\n4. Keep VM policy machine-checkable in every run artifact:\n   - require explicit no-network mode (`-nic none`, fallback `-net none`)\n   - require immutable OS image evidence when relevant (`readonly=on` on OS drive)\n5. For inference planning, keep GGUF parser behavior aligned to `ggml` spec before expanding model/backend scope.\n\n## Suggested compliance KPI (next 10 iterations)\n- Minimum 7/10 iterations must include core HolyC code changes (not docs-only).\n- Every iteration must include one deterministic validation command with expected output.\n- Zero iterations may run without explicit no-network VM evidence.\n\n## Links\n- https://wiki.osdev.org/Creating_an_Operating_System\n- https://wiki.osdev.org/Bare_Bones\n- https://wiki.osdev.org/Paging\n- https://pdos.csail.mit.edu/6.828/2025/xv6/book-riscv-rev5.pdf\n- https://docs.sel4.systems/projects/sel4/verified-configurations.html\n- https://www.qemu.org/docs/master/system/qemu-manpage.html\n- https://github.com/ggml-org/ggml/blob/master/docs/gguf.md\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
